					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Ser=
ies of units for volume measurement</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beer_barrels_galore.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
3/34/Beer_barrels_galore.jpg/500px-Beer_barrels_galore.jpg" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"340" height=3D"255" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"2048" data-file-height=3D"1536"></a><figcaption>Ale casks at a brewery =
in the UK. They are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_brewer=
y_cask_units#Firkin" title=3D"English brewery cask units">firkins</a>, each=
 holding 9 imperial gallons (41&nbsp;L), or a quarter of a UK beer barrel.<=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>barrel</b> is one of several <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Unit_of_volume" title=3D"Unit of volume">units of volume</a> applied in =
various contexts: there are dry barrels; fluid barrels, such as the British=
 beer barrel and American beer barrel; oil barrels, etc. For historical rea=
sons, the volumes of some barrel units are roughly double the volumes of ot=
hers; volumes in common use range approximately from 100 to 200 litres (22 =
to 44&nbsp;imp&nbsp;gal; 26 to 53&nbsp;US&nbsp;gal). In many connections, t=
he term <em><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drum_(container)" titl=
e=3D"Drum (container)"><i>drum</i></a></em> is used almost interchangeably =
with <i>barrel</i>.
</p><p>Since medieval times, the term <em><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Barrel" title=3D"Barrel">barrel</a></em> as a unit of measure has h=
ad various meanings throughout Europe, ranging from about 100&nbsp;litres t=
o about 1,000&nbsp;litres. The name was derived in medieval times from the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_language" title=3D"French l=
anguage">French</a> <span title=3D"French-language text"><i lang=3D"fr">bar=
il</i></span>, of unknown origin, but still in use, both in French and as d=
erivations in many other languages, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Italian_language" title=3D"Italian language">Italian</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polish_language" title=3D"Polish language=
">Polish</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish_language=
" title=3D"Spanish language">Spanish</a>. In most countries, such usage is =
obsolescent, having been superseded by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/SI_units" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI units">SI units</a>. As a =
result, the meaning of corresponding words and related concepts (vat, cask,=
 keg etc.) in other languages often refers to a physical container rather t=
han a known measure.
</p><p>In the international oil market context, however, prices in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_dollar" title=3D"United Sta=
tes dollar">United States dollars</a> per barrel are commonly used, and the=
 term is variously translated, often to derivations of the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin" title=3D"Latin">Latin</a> / <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germanic_languages" title=3D"Germanic languages">=
Germanic </a> root <i>fat</i> (for example <i>vat</i> or <i>Fass</i>).<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-isbn0-19-861271-0_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-isbn0-19-861271-0-1"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>In other commercial connections, barrel sizes, such as beer <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keg" title=3D"Keg">keg</a> volumes, are s=
tandardised in many countries.
</p>
