<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Fluid_barrel_in_the_US_and_=
UK">Fluid barrel in the US and UK</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DBarrel_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Fluid barrel in the US and UK"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Fluid barrels vary depending on what is being measured and where. In the=
 UK a beer barrel is 36 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_g=
allon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Imperial gallon">imperial gallons</a>=
 (43&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_gallon" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"US gallon">US&nbsp;gal</a>; 164&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Litre" title=3D"Litre">L</a>). In the US most fluid ba=
rrels (apart from oil) are 31.5 US gallons (26&nbsp;imp&nbsp;gal; 119&nbsp;=
L) (half a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hogshead" title=3D"Hogs=
head">hogshead</a>), but a beer barrel is 31 US gallons (26&nbsp;imp&nbsp;g=
al; 117&nbsp;L).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barr=
el_(unit)#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The size of beer <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Keg" title=3D"Keg">kegs</a> in the US is based loosely on =
fractions of the US beer barrel. When referring to beer barrels or kegs in =
many countries, the term may be used for the commercial package units indep=
endent of actual volume, where common range for professional use is 20=E2=
=80=9360&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liter" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Liter">L</a>, typically a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/DIN" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"DIN">DIN</a> or <i>Euro keg</=
i> of 50&nbsp;L.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=
