<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Definitions">Definitions</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBarrel_(unit)&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Definitions"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petroleum_industry" titl=
e=3D"Petroleum industry">oil industry</a>, one <b>barrel</b> (<a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_symbol" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Uni=
t symbol">unit symbol</a> <b>bbl</b>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Unit_of_volume" title=3D"Unit of volume">unit of volume</a> used f=
or measuring <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petroleum" title=3D"P=
etroleum">oil</a> defined as exactly 42 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/US_gallons" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"US gallons">US gallons</a>=
, approximately 159 liters,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NistB_10-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-NistB-=
10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>or 35 <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_gallon" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Imperial gallon">imperial gallons</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NistB_10=
-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(un=
it)#cite_note-NistB-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>According to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_P=
etroleum_Institute" title=3D"American Petroleum Institute">American Petrole=
um Institute</a> (API), a <b>standard barrel of oil</b> is the amount of oi=
l that would occupy a volume of exactly 1 barrel (158.99&nbsp;L) at referen=
ce temperature and pressure conditions of 60&nbsp;=C2=B0F (15.6&nbsp;=C2=B0=
C) and 14.696&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pound_per_squar=
e_inch" title=3D"Pound per square inch">psi</a> (101,325&nbsp;<a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal_(unit)" title=3D"Pascal (unit)">Pa</a>; =
1&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmosphere_(unit)" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Atmosphere (unit)">atm</a>). This standard barrel of=
 oil will occupy a different volume at different pressures and temperatures=
. A standard barrel in this context is thus not simply a measure of volume,=
 but of volume under specific conditions. (<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inl=
ine-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320"><span role=3D"note" =
class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable crossreference">See also: <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_temperature_and_pressure#Molar_=
volume_of_a_gas" title=3D"Standard temperature and pressure">Standard tempe=
rature and pressure#Molar volume of a gas</a>.</span>)
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Unit_multiples">Unit multip=
les</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBarrel_(=
unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Unit multip=
les"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>Oil companies that are publicly listed in the United States typically re=
port their production using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Un=
it_multiple" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unit multiple">unit multiples</=
a> <b>Mbbl</b> (one thousand barrels) and <b>MMbbl</b> (one million barrels=
), derived from the Latin word "mille" and Roman Numeral M, meaning "thousa=
nd". Due to the risk of confusion The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Society_of_Petroleum_Engineers" title=3D"Society of Petroleum Engineers=
">Society of Petroleum Engineers</a> recommends in their style guide that a=
bbreviations or prefixes M or MM are not used for barrels of oil or barrel =
of oil equivalent, but rather that thousands, millions or billions are spel=
led out.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Using M for thousand and MM for million are in conflict with the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units" title=
=3D"International System of Units">SI</a> convention where the "M" prefix s=
tands for "mega" representing million, from the Greek for "large". Some oil=
 companies, particularly those based in Europe, use <b>kb</b> (kilobarrels,=
 one thousand barrels), <b>mb</b> (megabarrels, one million barrels), and <=
b>gb</b> (gigabarrels, one billion barrels). The lower case m is used to av=
oid confusion with the capital M used for thousand. For the same reason, th=
e unit <b>kbbl</b> (one thousand barrels) is also sometimes used.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBarrel_(unit)&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The first "b" in "bbl" may have been doubled originally to indicate the =
plural (1 bl, 2 bbl), or possibly it was doubled to eliminate any confusion=
 with bl as a symbol for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paper=
_bale" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Paper bale">bale</a>. Some sources as=
sert that "bbl" originated as a symbol for "blue barrels" delivered by <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_Oil" title=3D"Standard Oil">S=
tandard Oil</a> in its early days. However, while Ida Tarbell's 1904 Standa=
rd Oil Company history acknowledged the "holy blue barrel", the abbreviatio=
n "bbl" had been in use well before the 1859 birth of the U.S. petroleum in=
dustry.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Flow_rate">Flow rate</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBarrel_(unit)&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Flow rate"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oil_wells" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Oil wells">Oil wells</a> recover not just oil from the ground, b=
ut also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_gas" title=3D"Natu=
ral gas">natural gas</a> and water. The term <b>barrels of liquid per day</=
b> (BLPD) refers to the total volume of liquid that is recovered.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Similarly, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_of_oil_equivalent" title=3D"Barrel of oil equivalen=
t">barrels of oil equivalent</a> or BOE is a value that accounts for both o=
il and natural gas while ignoring any water that is recovered. Other terms =
are used when discussing only oil. These terms can refer to either the prod=
uction of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crude_oil" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Crude oil">crude oil</a> at an oil well, the conversion o=
f crude oil to other products at an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Oil_refinery" title=3D"Oil refinery">oil refinery</a>, or the overall con=
sumption of oil by a region or country. One common term is <span class=3D"a=
nchor" id=3D"BOPD"></span><b>barrels per day</b> (BPD, BOPD, bbl/d, bpd, bd=
, or b/d), where 1&nbsp;BPD is equivalent to 0.0292&nbsp;<a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gallons_per_minute" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"G=
allons per minute">gallons per minute</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-statrev_15-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)=
#cite_note-statrev-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One BPD also becomes 49.8&nbsp;tonnes =
per year.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-statrev_15-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-statrev-15"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> At an oil refinery, production is sometimes reported as <b>barrels per ca=
lendar day</b> (b/cd or bcd), which is total production in a year divided b=
y the days in that year. Likewise, <b>barrels per stream day</b> (BSD or BP=
SD) is the quantity of oil product produced by a single refining unit durin=
g continuous operation for 24&nbsp;hours.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-=
17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>Burning one tonne of light, synthetic, or heavy crude yields 38.51, =
39.40, or 40.90&nbsp;GJ (thermal) respectively (10.70, 10.94, or 11.36&nbsp=
;MW=C2=B7h), so 1&nbsp;tonne per day of synthetic crude is about 456&nbsp;k=
W of thermal power and 1&nbsp;bpd of synthetic crude is about 378&nbsp;kW (=
slightly less for light crude, slightly more for heavy crude).<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bar=
rel_(unit)#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Conversion">Conversion</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBarrel_(unit)&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Conversion"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The task of converting a standard barrel of oil to a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_cubic_metre" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Standard cubic metre">standard cubic metre</a> of oil is complicated by the=
 fact that the latter is defined by the API to mean the amount of oil that,=
 at different reference conditions (101.325&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/KPa" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"KPa">kPa</a> and 15&nbsp=
;=C2=B0C (59.0&nbsp;=C2=B0F)), occupies 1&nbsp;cubic metre. The fact that t=
he reference conditions are not exactly the same means that an exact conver=
sion is impossible unless the exact expansion coefficient of the crude is k=
nown, and this will vary from one crude oil to another.
</p><p>For a light oil with density of 850&nbsp;kilogram per cubic metre (<=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/API_gravity" title=3D"API gravity">=
API gravity</a> of 35),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-19"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
warming the oil from 59&nbsp;=C2=B0F (15&nbsp;=C2=B0C) to 60&nbsp;=C2=B0F (=
16&nbsp;=C2=B0C) might increase its volume by about 0.047%. Conversely, a h=
eavy oil with a density of 934&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup> (API gravity of 20) mi=
ght only increase in volume by 0.039%. If physically measuring the density =
at a new temperature is not possible, then tables of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical_evidence" title=3D"Empirical evidence">empiric=
al data</a> can be used to accurately predict the change in density. In tur=
n, this allows maximum accuracy when converting between standard barrel and=
 standard cubic metre. The logic above also implies the same level of accur=
acy in measurements for barrels if there is a 1&nbsp;=C2=B0F (0.56&nbsp;=C2=
=B0C) error in measuring the temperature at time of measuring the volume.
</p><p>For ease of trading, communication and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Financial_accounting" title=3D"Financial accounting">financial =
accounting</a>, international commodity exchanges often set a conversion fa=
ctor for benchmark crude oils. For instance the conversion factor set by th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_Mercantile_Exchange" ti=
tle=3D"New York Mercantile Exchange">New York Mercantile Exchange</a> (NYME=
X) for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Canadian_Select" ti=
tle=3D"Western Canadian Select">Western Canadian Select</a> (WCS) crude oil=
 traded at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hardisty,_Alberta" titl=
e=3D"Hardisty, Alberta">Hardisty, Alberta</a>, Canada is 6.29287&nbsp;U.S. =
barrels per standard cubic metre,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-20"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> despite the uncertainty in converting the volume for crude oil. Reg=
ulatory authorities in producing countries set <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Allocation_(oil_and_gas)#Uncertainty_in_measures_and_allocatio=
n" title=3D"Allocation (oil and gas)">standards for measurement accuracy</a=
> of produced hydrocarbons, where such measurements affect taxes or royalti=
es to the government. In the United Kingdom, for instance, the measurement =
accuracy required is =C2=B10.25%.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-21"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Qualifiers">Qualifiers</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBarrel_(unit)&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Qualifiers"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A barrel can technically be used to specify any volume. Since the actual=
 nature of the fluids being measured varies along the stream, sometimes qua=
lifiers are used to clarify what is being specified. In the oil field, it i=
s often important to differentiate between rates of production of fluids, w=
hich may be a mix of oil and water, and rates of production of the oil itse=
lf. If a well is producing 10&nbsp;MBD (thousands of barrels per day) of fl=
uids with a 20% water cut, then the well would also be said to be producing=
 8,000&nbsp;barrels of oil a day (bod).
</p><p>In other circumstances, it can be important to include <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_gas" title=3D"Natural gas">gas</a> in p=
roduction and consumption figures. Normally, gas amount is measured in <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_cubic_feet" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Standard cubic feet">standard cubic feet</a> or <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_cubic_metre" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Standard cubic metre">standard cubic metres</a> (for volume at STP), =
as well as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kg" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Kg">kg</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Btu" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Btu">Btu</a> (which do not depend on pressur=
e or temperature). But when necessary, such volume is converted to a volume=
 of oil of equivalent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enthalpy" ti=
tle=3D"Enthalpy">enthalpy</a> of combustion. Production and consumption usi=
ng this analogue is stated in barrels of oil equivalent per day (boed).
</p><p>In the case of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_inject=
ion_(oil_production)" title=3D"Water injection (oil production)">water-inje=
ction</a> wells, in the United States it is common to refer to the injectiv=
ity rate in barrels of water per day (bwd). In Canada, it is measured in cu=
bic metres per day (m<sup>3</sup>/d). In general, water injection rates wil=
l be stated in the same units as oil production rates, since the usual obje=
ctive is to replace the volume of oil produced with a similar volume of wat=
er to maintain reservoir pressure.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Related_kinds_of_quantity">=
Related kinds of quantity</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DBarrel_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Related kinds of quantity"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Outside the United States, volumes of oil are usually reported in <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_metre" title=3D"Cubic metre">cubic=
 metres</a> (m<sup>3</sup>) instead of oil barrels. Cubic metre is the basi=
c volume unit in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International=
_system_of_units" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International system of un=
its">International System</a>. In Canada, oil companies measure oil in cubi=
c metres, but convert to barrels on export, since most of Canada's oil prod=
uction is exported to the US. The nominal conversion factor is 1&nbsp;cubic=
 metre =3D 6.2898&nbsp;oil barrels,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-22"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> but conversion is generally done by <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Custody_transfer" title=3D"Custody transfer">custody transfer</=
a> meters on the border, since the volumes are specified at different tempe=
ratures, and the exact conversion factor depends on both density and temper=
ature. Canadian companies operate internally and report to Canadian governm=
ents in cubic metres, but often convert to US&nbsp;barrels for the benefit =
of American investors and oil marketers. They generally quote prices in <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_dollar" title=3D"Canadian do=
llar">Canadian dollars</a> per cubic metre to other Canadian companies, but=
 use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_dollars" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"US dollars">US dollars</a> per barrel in financial reports an=
d press statements, making it appear to the outside world that they operate=
 in barrels.
</p><p>Companies on the European stock exchanges report the <i>mass</i> of =
oil in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tonne" title=3D"Tonne">tonn=
es</a>. Since different varieties of petroleum have different densities, ho=
wever, there is not a single conversion between mass and volume. For exampl=
e, one tonne of heavy distillates might occupy a volume of 6.1 barrels (970=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Litre" title=3D"Litre">litres</a>=
; 256 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_gallon" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"US gallon">US gallons</a>). In contrast, one tonne of crude o=
il might occupy 6.5 barrels (1,030 litres; 273 US gallons), and one tonne o=
f gasoline will require 7.9 barrels (1,260 litres; 332 US gallons).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Overall, the conversion is usual=
ly between 6 and 8 barrels (954 and 1,270 litres; 252 and 336 US gallons) p=
er tonne.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"History_2">History</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBarrel_(unit)&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The measurement of an "oil barrel" originated in the early <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pennsylvania" title=3D"Pennsylvania">Pennsylvan=
ia</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oil_field" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Oil field">oil fields</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Drake_Well" title=3D"Drake Well">Drake Well</a>, the first oil =
well in the US, was drilled in Pennsylvania in 1859, and an oil boom follow=
ed in the 1860s. When oil production began, there was no standard container=
 for oil, so oil and petroleum products were stored and transported in barr=
els of different shapes and sizes. Some of these barrels would originally h=
ave been used for other products, such as beer, fish, molasses, or turpenti=
ne. Both the 42-US-gallon (159&nbsp;L) barrels (based on the old English wi=
ne measure), the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_units_of_=
wine_casks#Tierce" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"English units of wine cas=
ks">tierce</a> (159&nbsp;litres) and the 40-US-gallon (150&nbsp;L) <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whiskey" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"W=
hiskey">whiskey</a> barrels were used. Also, 45-US-gallon (170&nbsp;L) barr=
els were in common use. The 40&nbsp;gallon whiskey barrel was the most comm=
on size used by early oil producers, since they were readily available at t=
he time.
</p><p>Around 1866, early oil producers in Pennsylvania concluded that ship=
ping oil in a variety of different containers was causing buyer distrust. T=
hey decided they needed a standard unit of measure to convince buyers that =
they were getting a fair volume for their money, and settled on the standar=
d wine <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tierce_(unit)" title=3D"Tie=
rce (unit)">tierce</a>, which was two gallons larger than the standard whis=
ky barrel. The <i>Weekly Register</i>, an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Oil_City,_Pennsylvania" title=3D"Oil City, Pennsylvania">Oil City, =
Pennsylvania</a> newspaper, stated on August 31, 1866 that "the oil produce=
rs have issued the following circular":
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p> Whereas, It is conceded by all prod=
ucers of crude petroleum on Oil Creek that the present system of selling cr=
ude oil by the barrel, without regard to the size, is injurious to the oil =
trade, alike to the buyer and seller, as buyers, with an ordinary sized bar=
rel cannot compete with those with large ones. We, therefore, mutually agre=
e and bind ourselves that from this date we will sell no crude by the barre=
l or package, but by the gallon only. An allowance of two gallons will be m=
ade on the gauge of each and every 40&nbsp;gallons in favor of the buyer.</=
p></blockquote>
<p>And by that means, King Richard&nbsp;III's English wine tierce became th=
e American standard oil barrel.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-24"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>By 1872, the standard oil barrel was firmly established as 42&nbsp;U=
S-gallons.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The 42&nbsp;gal=
lon standard oil barrel was officially adopted by the Petroleum Producers A=
ssociation in 1872 and by the U.S. Geological Survey and the U.S. Bureau of=
 Mines in 1882.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-oilbblhist_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#cite_note-oilbblhist-9">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>In modern times, many different types of oil, chemicals, and other p=
roducts are transported in steel <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
rum_(container)#International_standard_size" title=3D"Drum (container)">dru=
ms</a>. In the United States, these commonly have a capacity of 55 US gallo=
ns (208&nbsp;L) and are referred to as such. They are called 200&nbsp;litre=
 or 200&nbsp;kg drums outside the United States. In the United Kingdom and =
its former dependencies, a 44-imperial-gallon (200&nbsp;L) drum was used, e=
ven though all those countries now officially use the metric system and the=
 drums are filled to 200&nbsp;litres. In the United States, the 42&nbsp;US-=
gallon size as a unit of measure is largely confined to the oil industry, w=
hile different sizes of barrel are used in other industries. Nearly all oth=
er countries use the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_system=
" title=3D"Metric system">metric system</a>.
</p><p>Thus, the 42&nbsp;US-gallon oil barrel is a unit of measure rather t=
han a physical container used to transport crude oil.
</p>
